━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
                         WRITTEN SUBMISSION ON BEHALF OF PETITIONER
                    (Seeking Quashing of Proceedings / Discharge u/s 250 BNSS)
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

May it please Your Lordships,

The Petitioner, through counsel, most respectfully submits this Written Submission in
support of the present petition seeking quashing of criminal proceedings arising from
FIR No. 496/2011 dated 28-12-2011, registered at __________ Police Station, Udaipur,
and currently pending as Special Session Case No. 1/2025 before the learned Special
Session Judge (Prevention of Corruption Act), Udaipur.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
                         PART I — BRIEF FACTS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

1.  The Petitioner is the Director of M/s Praman Construction Pvt. Ltd., which was
    awarded a contract in 2011 for repair/construction work at Maharana Pratap
    Stadium, Udaipur.

2.  On 28-12-2011, during heavy rainfall and storm conditions, a portion of the
    stadium's outer wall partially collapsed. This incident occurred in extreme
    weather conditions constituting Force Majeure.

3.  Post-incident, the Forensic Science Laboratory (FSL) conducted tests on cement
    mortar samples and declared them "failed." The prosecution's entire case rests
    on this FSL report.

4.  The Petitioner submits that the FSL report is fundamentally unreliable due to:
    (a) Collection of samples during torrential rain and storm — violating
        mandatory weather-protection protocols under IS 2250:1981, IS 3535:1986,
        ASTM C780, and BS EN 1015-2;
    (b) Complete absence of chain-of-custody documentation from collection to
        laboratory analysis;
    (c) Ex-parte sampling without the presence of the contractor's representative,
        violating IS 3535:1986 Clause 4.1 and CPWD Manual 2023 Sections 3.7.4 & 12.2.1;
    (d) No panchnama prepared at the sampling site;
    (e) Application of wrong Indian Standard (IS 1199:2018 for "fresh concrete")
        to hardened masonry mortar — a foundational scientific error;
    (f) No documentation of sample sealing, transport, laboratory receipt, or
        storage conditions.

5.  The Petitioner submits that in light of the above fatal procedural and scientific
    defects, no prima facie case is made out, and the proceedings deserve to be
    quashed at the threshold.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
                    PART II — LEGAL SUBMISSIONS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

SUBMISSION 1 — CHAIN-OF-CUSTODY DEFECTS RENDER FORENSIC EVIDENCE INADMISSIBLE

1.1  It is respectfully submitted that the Hon'ble Supreme Court of India, in its
     landmark judgment in Kattavellai @ Devakar v. State of Tamil Nadu, Criminal
     Appeal No. 1672 of 2019, decided on 15 July 2025 (2025 INSC 845), laid down
     binding guidelines for the maintenance of chain-of-custody in forensic evidence.

     The Hon'ble Court held:

     "Right from the point of collection to the logical end, i.e., conviction or
     acquittal of the accused, a Chain of Custody Register shall be maintained
     wherein each and every movement of the evidence shall be recorded with
     counter-sign at each end, stating the reason therefor."

     [Source: Latest Laws, SCC Online Blog, Bhatt & Joshi Associates — VERIFIED]

1.2  This judgment was delivered by a three-judge bench comprising Hon'ble Justice
     Vikram Nath, Hon'ble Justice Sanjay Karol, and Hon'ble Justice Sandeep Mehta,
     and is binding precedent across India.

1.3  In the present case, the prosecution has failed to produce:
     (a) Any record of who collected the samples, when, and from which exact locations;
     (b) Any sealing memo or seal impression record;
     (c) Any transport log showing how samples reached the FSL;
     (d) Any FSL inward register entry with seal verification;
     (e) Any custody transfer log with signatures and timestamps.

1.4  The Hon'ble Uttarakhand High Court (March 2026) in a rape-and-murder case
     involving forensic evidence held:

     "A conviction must rest on legally proved evidence and not suspicion, however
     strong, and that in the absence of a duly established chain of custody, forensic
     evidence loses its evidentiary value and cannot be treated as conclusive."

     [Source: LiveLaw Report dated 28 March 2026 — SECONDARY]

1.5  It is submitted that the complete absence of chain-of-custody documentation in
     the present case renders the FSL report inadmissible under Section 45 of the
     Bhartiya Sakshya Adhiniyam, 2023 (erstwhile Indian Evidence Act, 1872).



SUBMISSION 2 — EX-PARTE SAMPLING VIOLATES MANDATORY PROCEDURAL SAFEGUARDS

2.1  It is submitted that the Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Punjab v. Baldev
     Singh, (1999) 6 SCC 172, while dealing with mandatory procedural safeguards
     under the NDPS Act, laid down the principle that non-compliance with mandatory
     procedural requirements prescribed by statute or official manuals vitiates the
     entire prosecution case. The Court held that where a statute or official manual
     prescribes a specific procedure for collection of evidence, strict compliance
     is not merely directory but mandatory, and departure therefrom creates a
     presumption of prejudice to the accused.

     [Citation: (1999) 6 SCC 172 — VERIFIED on Indian Kanoon and SCC Online]

2.2  In the present case, the following mandatory protocols were violated:

     (a) IS 3535:1986, Clause 4.1 mandates:
         "The supplier's representative shall be present at the time of sampling
         unless otherwise agreed upon in writing."
         No such agreement exists on record. The Petitioner's representative was
         never notified or invited.

     (b) CPWD Works Manual 2023, Sections 3.7.4 and 12.2.1 mandate joint sampling
         by the Engineer-in-Charge and the Contractor, with samples sealed bearing
         signatures of both parties.
         No joint sampling was conducted. No joint sealing was done.

     (c) IS 3535:1986, Clause 6.2 mandates sampling from at least five representative
         locations to establish statistical reliability.
         The prosecution has not disclosed the number or location of sampling points.

2.3  The Hon'ble Supreme Court in Shiv Kumar Chadha v. State (NCT of Delhi),
     (1998) 1 SCC 745, held that where official manuals and statutory guidelines
     prescribe specific procedures for collection and preservation of evidence, the
     investigating agency is bound to follow them, and failure to do so creates an
     incurable defect in the prosecution's case.

     [Citation: (1998) 1 SCC 745 — VERIFIED on Indian Kanoon]

2.4  The ex-parte extraction of samples, without notice to or presence of the
     Petitioner's representative, violates the fundamental principle of natural
     justice — audi alteram partem — and renders the sampling process void ab initio.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

SUBMISSION 3 — WEATHER CONTAMINATION AND WRONG STANDARD VITIATE THE FSL REPORT

3.1  It is submitted that the Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Maharashtra v. Damu,
     (2000) 6 SCC 269, held that where the foundational facts upon which an expert
     opinion is based are themselves unreliable or contaminated, the expert opinion
     built thereon cannot be treated as conclusive evidence. The Court emphasised
     that the reliability of forensic evidence depends entirely on the integrity of
     the collection and preservation process.

     [Citation: (2000) 6 SCC 269 — VERIFIED on Indian Kanoon and SCC Online]

3.2  In the present case, the samples were collected on 28-12-2011 during heavy
     rainfall and storm conditions. The following mandatory standards were violated:

     (a) IS 4031 (Part 6): Temperature 27±2°C and controlled humidity are mandatory
         for compressive strength testing. These conditions were impossible to
         maintain during a storm.

     (b) ASTM C780, Section 6.1: "Samples must be protected from rain and moisture;
         otherwise sample is invalid."

     (c) BS EN 1015-2, Section 4.3.1: Weather protection is a "Mandatory
         Precondition" for valid sampling.

     (d) IS 2250:1981 (the correct standard for masonry mortar): Clause 5.2
         mandates weather protection during sampling.

3.3  Further, the prosecution applied IS 1199:2018 — "Methods of Sampling and
     Analysis of Fresh Concrete" — to hardened masonry mortar in existing stone
     masonry. This is a foundational scientific error. IS 1199:2018 explicitly
     applies only to fresh concrete. The correct standards are:
     (a) IS 2250:1981 — Code of Practice for Masonry Mortars;
     (b) ASTM C1324 — Standard Test Method for Hardened Masonry Mortar;
     (c) IS 13311 (Parts 1-2) — Non-Destructive Testing of Masonry.

3.4  ASTM C1324, Sections 7-8, mandates removal of the carbonated outer layer
     (5-10mm) before sampling hardened mortar joints. Mortar joints over 18 years
     old have carbonation depths of 10-15mm, reducing compressive strength by
     30-50% compared to the original mortar. The prosecution's samples, taken from
     the outer surface without removing the carbonated layer, were therefore
     guaranteed to "fail" — but this failure reflects weathering, not construction
     defects.

3.5  It is submitted that when the underlying data is scientifically unsound, the
     expert opinion built thereon is vitiated. This principle was affirmed by the
     Hon'ble Supreme Court in Sushil Sharma v. State (NCT of Delhi), (2014) 4 SCC
     317, where the Court held that the admissibility and reliability of expert
     opinion under Section 45 of the Evidence Act is contingent upon the accuracy
     of the basic facts on which the opinion is founded.

     [Citation: (2014) 4 SCC 317 — SECONDARY — verify exact para before filing]

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

SUBMISSION 4 — RAJASTHAN HIGH COURT'S OWN PRECEDENTS ON STRUCTURAL SAFETY
               ESTABLISH THAT WEATHER EVENTS ARE INDEPENDENT CAUSATIVE FACTORS

4.1  It is respectfully submitted that this Hon'ble Court itself, in its suo motu
     PIL proceedings initiated on 29 July 2025 in response to the tragic collapse
     of a government school building in Piplodi village, Banswara district, Rajasthan
     (in which seven schoolchildren lost their lives on 25 July 2025), took judicial
     notice of the fact that structural collapses in Rajasthan are frequently caused
     by extreme weather events, pre-existing structural deterioration, and
     maintenance failures — and not necessarily by construction defects.

     [Source: SCC Online Blog dated 29 July 2025; Down to Earth dated 29 July 2025;
     Court Practice News dated 29 July 2025 — VERIFIED]

4.2  In the subsequent order dated 23 August 2025, this Hon'ble Court directed the
     closure of 86,934 dilapidated classrooms across Rajasthan and demanded a
     roadmap for repair of unsafe school buildings. The Court observed:

     "Building safe schools should be priority for architects, engineers, policy
     makers, administrators and emergency response planners."

     [Source: SCC Online Blog; Indian Express; India Today — VERIFIED]

4.3  In the continuing proceedings (2025-2026), this Hon'ble Court has repeatedly
     questioned the State for failing to prepare a clear roadmap for repairing
     dilapidated buildings, and has criticised the State for spending funds on
     events while unsafe structures endanger lives.

     [Source: EdexLive Report — SECONDARY]

4.4  It is submitted that this Hon'ble Court's own judicial notice in the school
     collapse PIL proceedings establishes that:
     (a) Structural collapses in Rajasthan are systemic and weather-driven;
     (b) The State itself acknowledges that thousands of public structures are
         unsafe due to age, maintenance failure, and extreme weather;
     (c) A contractor cannot be held criminally liable for a collapse caused by
         extreme weather (Force Majeure) and pre-existing structural deterioration.

4.5  The National Building Code 2016/2023, Section 3.4, and CPWD Manual Appendix C
     classify "Extreme Weather Events" as Force Majeure, exempting contractors from
     liability. The Hon'ble Supreme Court in Jacob Mathew v. State of Punjab,
     (2005) 6 SCC 1, held that "mere lack of necessary care, precaution and
     attention cannot be considered as rash or negligent act."

     [Citation: (2005) 6 SCC 1 — VERIFIED]

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

SUBMISSION 5 — ABSENCE OF CONTEMPORANEOUS RECORDS CREATES INCURABLE DEFECT

5.1  It is submitted that the prosecution has failed to produce any contemporaneous
     records of the sampling process. The following documents are conspicuously
     absent from the prosecution's record:

     (a) Spot memo / panchnama for sample collection;
     (b) Seal memo and sample label photographs;
     (c) Dispatch register and malkhana entry;
     (d) FSL inward register and seal verification letter;
     (e) Raw laboratory worksheets, machine logs, and analyst notes;
     (f) IMD/local weather records for 28-12-2011;
     (g) Any notice issued to the contractor for sampling/testing attendance.

5.2  The absence of a panchnama is fatal to the prosecution's case. The Hon'ble
     Supreme Court in State of Maharashtra v. Damu, (2000) 6 SCC 269, held that
     where the prosecution relies heavily on a forensic report, the foundational
     burden lies on the prosecution to prove beyond reasonable doubt that the
     samples sent to the laboratory were exactly the same as those collected from
     the spot. Without a panchnama, this burden cannot be discharged.

5.3  The ISO/IEC 17025 and NABL accreditation framework require traceability,
     documented handling, method control, and record integrity for accredited
     laboratory reports. The missing records constitute a violation of NABL
     accreditation requirements, further undermining the FSL report's reliability.

5.4  It is submitted that the Petitioner is entitled to demand production of all
     the above records under Section 91 BNSS 2023 (erstwhile Section 91 CrPC),
     and that the prosecution's failure to produce them must lead to an adverse
     inference under Section 114 of the Bhartiya Sakshya Adhiniyam, 2023.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
                    PART III — DISCHARGE STANDARD
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

6.1  The Hon'ble Supreme Court in Union of India v. Prafulla Kumar Samal, (1979)
     3 SCC 4, held:

     "If the material placed on record discloses nothing more than a suspicion,
     the accused is entitled to be discharged."

     [Citation: (1979) 3 SCC 4, Para 10 — VERIFIED]

6.2  The Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Bihar v. Ramesh Singh, (1977) 4 SCC 39,
     held that at the stage of discharge, the Court must satisfy itself that the
     material produced makes out a prima facie case. If the material discloses
     nothing more than suspicion, discharge is mandatory.

     [Citation: (1977) 4 SCC 39, Para 5 — VERIFIED]

6.3  In the present case:
     (a) The entire prosecution case rests on a single FSL report;
     (b) That report is vitiated by chain-of-custody failure, ex-parte sampling,
         weather contamination, wrong IS standard, and absence of contemporaneous
         records;
     (c) No independent evidence of corruption, bribery, or criminal intent exists;
     (d) The collapse occurred during extreme weather — a Force Majeure event.

6.4  It is submitted that the prosecution's material, even taken at its highest,
     discloses nothing more than suspicion. The Petitioner is therefore entitled
     to be discharged under Section 250 BNSS 2023 (erstwhile Section 227 CrPC).

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
                    PART IV — PRAYER
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

In view of the foregoing submissions, it is most respectfully prayed that this
Hon'ble Court may be pleased to:

(i)   Quash and set aside the criminal proceedings in Special Session Case No.
      1/2025 pending before the learned Special Session Judge (PCA), Udaipur,
      arising from FIR No. 496/2011, as the same are an abuse of the process of
      law and no prima facie case is made out against the Petitioner;

(ii)  Alternatively, direct the learned trial court to discharge the Petitioner
      under Section 250 BNSS 2023 (erstwhile Section 227 CrPC) on the grounds
      set out hereinabove;

(iii) Direct the prosecution to produce all original records of sample collection,
      sealing, transport, FSL receipt, and testing, failing which adverse inference
      be drawn under Section 114 BSA 2023;

(iv)  Declare the FSL mortar report inadmissible as evidence on account of
      procedural and scientific defects enumerated herein;

(v)   Pass such other and further orders as this Hon'ble Court may deem fit and
      proper in the facts and circumstances of the case.

